why there is a penalty for not using a model from the fixed list of models

Hello all, @deleted-role 

The release/0.4.0 branch is now locked in with new features, and we are ready to launch the update at the planned release time Wednesday, March 20, 2024 9:00 AM. We are still continuing the testing for the next couple of days so there may be some minor changes we commit, but no new features will be added. Miners should take the following into account in preparation for release:

There are four major changes to take into account:
-Vector Search Engine validation has been added to the validators. This means the miners must produce results that are verifiable by the validators, which on a practical level means the distance functions and embedding models used by the chromadb must be included in the response and be on the list of pre-approved models and distance functions. This increases the resource requirements on the validators slightly, so validators should monitor their CPU/RAM usage after the update and adjust resources if needed.
-Sensitive Information analyzer and token classification engine has been added for the miners. During the initial phase, not much is done with the analyzer apart from letting the miners to get used to the concept. We won't be serving prompts for the sensitive information analyzer that have an impact on the score, so it is not yet necessary to start fine-tuning it. We'll announce when we enter the next phase (most likely with the release of v0.5.0)
-Miners will be fetching the prompts from a fetch API (part of the prompting API), so they'll need to be able to open outbounds HTTPs connections towards the API.
-Validators must send validation results to a logger API, so they'll need to be able to open outbounds HTTPs connections towards the API. We're building a dashboard to monitor the subnet overall performance as well as provide the miners insights into their validation results. We're looking into options of allowing access to the raw logs for all the miners to even out the playing field.

Hello @deleted-role 

We have a few updates coming soon with subnet `v0.8.0`, and we feel that we should notify everyone ahead of time as there are a few major changes coming. 

1. We will start to release prompts for the **Sensitive Information Analyzer**,  so we advise that **miners start fine-tuning their Token Classification Engines now to prepare for the new analyzer.** The initial release will ask miners to detect the following types of sensitive information within a block of text. We will be formatting them both validly and invalidly and scoring miners on their ability to detect valid instances of the data type. The first five data types we will be releasing are:

- Email addresses
- IPv4 addresses
- IPv6 addresses
- US Social Security Numbers
- GitHub Personal Access Tokens

We have released a training dataset on HuggingFace here:
https://huggingface.co/datasets/synapsecai/synthetic-sensitive-information

2. We will be making changes to our scoring mechanism for miners that will affect the incentive distribution. The main points are:

- Penalizing false positives more heavily and penalizing false negatives less heavily, 
- Normalizing scores using the distribution `abs(ln(x))` and binning those values according to the following bins:
```
abs(ln(x)) = 0 to 0.03: score of 1,
abs(ln(x)) = 0.03 to 0.11: score of 0.9,
abs(ln(x)) = 0.11 to 0.22: score of 0.8,
abs(ln(x)) = 0.22 to 0.35: score of 0.7,
abs(ln(x)) = 0.35 to 0.51: score of 0.6,
abs(ln(x)) = 0.51 to 0.69: score of 0.5,
abs(ln(x)) = 0.69 to 0.91: score of 0.4,
abs(ln(x)) = 0.91 to 1.2: score of 0.3,
abs(ln(x)) = 1.2 to 1.6: score of 0.2,
abs(ln(x)) = 1.6 to 2.3: score of 0.1
abs(ln(x)) >= 2.3: score of 0.0
```

Hello @deleted-role 

We have a few important updates coming up, and we feel it is necessary to go into full detail about the upcoming changes.

# TL;DR
In the previous release (v0.8.0) and the upcoming releases (v0.9.0 and v1.0.0), we'll be introducing game-breaking changes to adjust the way the subnet behaves. The changes are aimed to increase the competitiveness, reduce gamification and prevent abuse of the centralized aspects of the subnet. These changes fall under three major categories which correlate with different release versions:

- Scoring algorithm renewal (v0.8.0), which we hope will increase the level of competition in the subnet and hopefully attract more miners to join the subnet. This version has already been released and has already led to a much more competetive incentive curve, which you can view here: https://x.taostats.io/subnet/14#distribution
- Decommissioning of centralized components (v0.9.0), which will make the subnet **entirely decentralized.** Validators will need to adjust their hardware requirements at this point since these changes involve generating prompts locally to feed to miners.
- Improvements on base models and production launch (v1.0.0)

In this post, we'll be going over the changes and provide additional insights on the objectives of the changes.

# Scoring Algorithm renewal (v0.8.0) - Current Release
The old scoring algorithm was relatively simple and was based on purely on the accuracy of the analysis and the speed of the response, with the accuracy consisting 85% of the overall score. This caused a situation in which the incentive distribution between miners with similar level of performance was close to each other, and typically almost all miners had an incentive between 0.0041 and 0.0043. The close distribution caused various issues for miners. The most prominent issues were seemingly random de-registrations and huge decrease in the incentive in case of temporary performance degradation that caused miners to de-register even though they should have not been deregistered. The flat distribution and fine margins also enabled the possibility of a malicious validator to elevate certain miners above others, in the expense of their vtrust, making the miners practically immune for competition.

In the previous release (v0.8.0), the scoring algorithm was adjusted. The details of the scoring algorithm are documented at https://docs.synapsec.ai/Reward%20Mechanism/scoring/

Here is a brief summary of the changes:

- The performance of the miner is still assessed based on the accuracy of the analysis and the speed of response, but the score normalization and scaling has been adjusted significantly.
- Miners are placed in performance buckets based on their relative analysis accuracy and are assigned a score based on their performance bucket.
- Score is based on historical performance and is calculated every time the validator is setting weights. During the evaluation, empty responses are ignored and the performance is calculated based only on the valid responses received from the miners.
- Specialization bonuses are applied for the top miners for each analyzer. This allows a miner to focus only on a single analyzer and still be able to be considered a miner eligible to be placed in the top buckets. 
- The score originating from the performance bucket is combined with the score for the speed of the response, which separates the miners with relatively similar performance based on the speed of the response.
- Penalties are applied based on unwanted analysis behavior. Currently, we want to discourage false-positive analysis but we'll be adjusting this in future releases based on how the miner performance evolves.
- The resulting scores are normalized and power-scaled to result in a larger distribution in incentive for the miners. Currently we are observing miner incentives to be in range 0.0087 and 0.0004, while most miners being in range 0.0032 and 0.0059.

The objective of the scoring algorithm renewal was to increase the difference in incentives for miners with similar performance to better incentivize the miners to search for small incremental performance improvements and disincentive running multiple miners, as the miner gains have much higher level of diminishing returns due to them being distributed further away from each other. We hope that these changes will increase the level of competition in the subnet and hopefully attract more miners to join.

# Patch Releases (v0.8.Z)
Between the minor releases, we are releasing couple of patch releases to introduce the following new functionalities:

- Weight commit + reveal functionality
- Reference implementation for the Subnet API (docker container + terraform configuration)
- Bulk analyzer to analyze 100+ prompts at the same time
- Minor changes to scoring algorithm:  if more than 5% of the responses for a given miner stored in the validator cache are empty, a gradually increasing penalty is applied. This allows miners to be restarted or otherwise have small amount of downtime without receiving a decrease in the incentive.

Weight commit + reveal functionality is an essential update in the efforts to find weights to combat weight copying, and is something we want to add into the subnet as soon as possible, especially considering the other changes we have planned out (removal of decentralized components).

With the reference implementation for the Subnet API, any validator can run their own private API and integrate into the subnet and easily protect their LLM-based applications. The reference implementation will also mark a level of production stability for our subnet and as a result, we have been discussing with OTF about the inclusion of the subnet API in their upcoming API marketplace. This will enable web2 users to utilize the subnet to protect their LLM workloads, enabling us to reach much wider audience and thus bring additional value into the Bittensor ecosystem.

In addition to the API marketplace, we'll be hosting our own non-production grade API for the Bittensor community to utilize for development and testing purposes. 

The bulk analyzer API expands the subnet functionality to enable the possibility to analyze large datasets with the analyzers. This for example enables the scrubbing of datasets from sensitive information before being used as a part of the model fine-tuning.

# Decommissioning of centralized components (v0.9.0)
Another big change we would like to announce is the decommissioning of the centralized components (Prompt and Logger APIs) to make the subnet **entirely decentralized**. We have reached a state in the subnet development process where we feel that we are comfortable decreasing the level of centralization without affecting the quality of the subnet. The decommissioning also entirely removes the possibility for us to abuse the centralized components for personal gain.

Currently, the Prompt API is used to generate the prompts miners are tasked to analyze, and the analysis results are shipped to the Logger API to create the metrics dashboard.

Ultimately, we believe all things in Bittensor-ecosystem should be decentralized and eventually decentralizing the components was always our plan. However, we decided to decentralize the components a bit faster than originally expected due to the feedback we received from the community.

Initially we decided to utilize centralized components from two primary reasons:

- As we are dealing with malicious prompts, several services and LLM models forbid the creation of such content. For example, OpenAI, Corcel and locally running models such as LLaMA have Terms of Service (ToS) that prevent us from using them to generate the prompts. By using permissive open source models (for example Mixtral) or generating the malicious prompts in chunks, we were able to use the centralized prompt generation to have a cost-effective solution for the prompt generation without validators having to worry about possible ToS violations.
- To keep the prompt generation as a separate development track from subnet development. This allowed us to rapidly make adjustments to the prompts issued to the subnet to address specific issues we observed in miner behavior. We were also able to experiment with different system prompts without causing constant updates to be applied for the validators, which significantly decreased the effort required to run the validators.

With release v0.9.0, we are removing all centralized components that could potentially be abused or are otherwise not justified. This means that we'll be removing both the Prompt API and the Logger API. 

The removal of the Prompt API introduces significant changes for the validators:

- Validators must have a GPU and in total have approximately 80GB VRAM. 
- We have not yet finalized the hardware requirements, but have been testing the new validator version in Amazon Web Services (AWS) using g5.12xlarge instance running the AMI "Deep Learning Base OSS Nvidia Driver GPU AMI (Ubuntu 22.04)".
- It is likely we'll be recommending validators to use this configuration or otherwise similar configuration.
- The subnet validator will be moved to be running only in a container.
- Validators must also be running a vLLM container with a fine-tuned version of Mixtral-8x7B.
- We'll provide a docker compose file for validators to run both of these containers.
- Validators will be using the locally running vLLM container to perform the same activities we are currently performing in the Prompt API (i.e., generate the prompts).

We'll provide approximately one week notice prior to the upgrade. Our recommendation is to do a complete re-installation of the instance used to run the validator before the update window and test the validator using testnet. We'll provide extended support hours before, during and after the update has been released. We also urge all validators who we haven't yet setup a support group to contact us to establish a support group.

Regarding the Logger API, we'll also be temporarily decommissioning it with the v0.9.0 release. This unfortunately means that we will be decommissioning the metrics dashboard. To counter the negative effects of the decommissioning, we'll be adding a feedback synapse to the validation loop, which we will be used to send feedback to the miner about the analysis results. This way miners get first-hand information about their performance, that is aimed to help miners to fine-tune their performance.

Our plan is to eventually re-introduce the metrics dashboard in some form, but we'll have to figure out a way to do it in a transparent and decentralized way.

# Improvements on the base-models and production launch (v1.0.0)
Currently we feel the barrier of entry to mine in the subnet is too high. Thus far the base miner has relied on open-source models, which are ineffective given the current prompts, and our objective is to make it much easier for miners to start mining in the subnet. 

We still want the subnet to reward miners that invest time and resources into their fine-tuning and environment optimization, but once we have released v0.9.0, we'll start to work on improving the base models and we'll be releasing fine-tuned base models that will hopefully perform significantly better than the current open-source models. The objective is to have models that are competitive, but are still behind in performance when compared to the top miners. We'll also be implementing additional changes that are targeting to make it easier for new miners to join the subnet.

We have not yet locked in the exact actions we plan to take to decrease the barrier of entry, so any feedback is highly appreciated. In addition to the base models, we'll most likely focus on better documentation, simpler miner structure, better logging capabilities, performance, stability and other quality-of-life topics. But as said, we haven't locked in the actions yet and we'll let the community know more about these in the near future.

Other changes we have planned for v1.0.0 are mostly quality-of-life, performance and stability adjustment. The objective is to make the subnet code and the neurons (validators, miners) easier to maintain, debug and upgrade, essentially increasing the production readiness of the subnet.

# Future plans (v1.Y.Z)
Once the subnet is production-ready, we will focus on increasing its capabilities further. For now, what is set in stone is the following:

- Increasing the variance in prompts fed to the Prompt Injection and Sensitive Information analyzers. For prompt injections, this will involve adding new system instructions for the models run by the validators, or further fine-tuning the model itself. For sensitive information prompts, we will focus on adding more data types to be analyzed and detected by miners.
- Adding a third analyzer to the subnet--the Moderation Analyzer, which will aim to mirror the capabilities of OpenAI’s Moderation API endpoint (https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/moderation). The task for miners with this analyzer will be to detect harmful/hateful content.

Apologies for the huge wall of text, we sincerely appreciate if you got through it all. There was just so much to cover.

Let us know if you have any questions or concerns regarding the above.

Cheers!

Hello @deleted-role 

We are launching subnet v0.9.0 roughly at Wednesday, July 24, 2024 7:00 AM. This is a major update for the subnet and requires both the validators and miners to update to the latest version. The update removes centralized components and fundamentally changes how the validators are issuing prompts to the subnet miners.

The release window will be confirmed ~24 hours prior to the release. After the update has been released, we'll be monitoring the stability closely and are on a high alert to support the community with any troubleshooting or issues you may face with the new update. We will set the `weights_version` hyperparameter to `90` immediately after the update has been launched and are prepared to close the registrations if the situation looks like it.

Between now and the release, we keep our validator and miner running 24/7 in testnet (netuid 38) to help with the testing of the new changes. For the next seven days, we have reserved additional time to help the community with the testing of the new release. In case you experience issues with the release, please feel free to reach out to our team directly or post a message to this discord channel. 

When doing the testing, ensure you're working with the release branch (`release/0.9.0-1`).

## Preliminary release notes
* Add container image generation workflows for validator
* Remove centralized components (remote logger, prompt API)
* Add support for decentralized prompt generation using vLLM (either local container or remote endpoint)
* Add healthcheck API for validators
* Added feedback synapse to provide the miners instant feedback about their analysis
* Modified prompt generation to generate a fresh prompt for each iteration
* Modified prompt generation for sensitive information to utilize vLLM
* Removed auto-updater to enhance the level of security by preventing unauthorized code execution via subnet updates
* Added wrapper for logging to enhance the native logging capabilities

Pull request is available at: https://github.com/synapsec-ai/llm-defender-subnet/pull/71

## Miners
Miners must take the following changes into account:
* Additional content added to the sensitive information analyzer (see the previous announcement: https://discord.com/channels/799672011265015819/1182422353360195695/1261487097509052527)
* Prompts are now generated locally on the validators and a different model is used for generating the prompts. We have also adjusted the system instructions to better suit the model. On a practical level, this means the prompts are slightly different compared to what they have been previously. We'll release a sample dataset generated with the new prompt generation method ~1 week after the release.
* Metrics dashboard will be decommissioned. Validators will now send a FeedbackSynapse after the PayloadSynapse has been handled, which provides a feedback loop for miners to better evaluate their performance.

## Validators
To support the new validator and the hardware requirements associated with it, validators must do a complete redeployment of the infrastructure. The following changes are applied:
- Validator is now running in a container
- Validator must use either a local vLLM or a remote vLLM endpoint to generate prompts
- As a result of the two above points, validators now have new hardware requirements: https://github.com/synapsec-ai/llm-defender-subnet/blob/release/0.9.0-1/min_compute.yml

We have published a guide for the validator setup at: https://docs.synapsec.ai/Validating/running_decentralized_validator/

The guide mentions two computing environments (AWS and DataCrunch) and hardware configurations we have tested the validator with. **These are examples we know the validator is working with, but it is not mandatory to run the validator either in AWS or DataCrunch.**

When running the validator in testnet, you should **always** use to the docker compose services with the `-dev` suffix and ensure you have defined the `--build` flag to build the container image locally.

To test the validator, follow the setup guide. Here is a TL;DR of the commands to run once the environment has been setup:
```
$ cd llm-defender-subnet
$ git pull
$ git checkout release/0.9.0-1
$ docker compose up llm-defender-validator-dev --build --force-recreate -d
$ docker compose logs -f --tail 10
```

Hello @deleted-role 

We are changing our update practices starting with the next release (v0.9.2).

TL;DR: Updates are pushed to main branch more frequently and validators must update within 48 hours of the release announcement by launching new tagged container. In case there are changes requiring coordination, we provide 48h notice and update must be done immediately after release. Miners should launch from tags rather than main branch (i.e., if latest release is v0.9.2, checkout to tags/v0.9.2 and launch).

Since the validator has been moved to a container and auto-updater has been deprecated, we'll be able to push incremental updates directly into the main branch of the subnet repository. This will decrease the effort we need to put into release process and should speed up the development efforts of the subnet.

Key highlights are the following:
- Patch releases (0.0.X) will always be compatible with the same minor release (0.X.0) and will not contain breaking changes or any large adjustments to miner scoring algorithms.
- Patch releases are made without a prior notice and in case we need to adjust the `weights_version` hyperparameter, validators are given at least 48 hours to launch the updated container image
- Minor releases can contain large adjustments to miner scoring algorithms or new miner features that require an coordinated update. If minor release contains changes requiring coordinated update from validators and/or miners, the update is announced 48 hours in advance. 
- If minor release doesn't contain large adjustments to miner scoring algorithms or new miner features, the release practice follows the same practice as the patch releases do.
- Breaking changes are reserved for major updates (X.0.0) and these will not be merged to main branch before the release is finalized
- The main branch will be the "latest development version" - it will work in mainnet, but may behave differently compared to rest of the neurons using the tagged releases.

We strongly suspect that the cause may be related to the general usage of Subtensor. We've noticed that after several repeated attempts to process the same block, it is possible that the Subtensor node temporarily blocks further actions.

Each time you call `metagraph.sync`, it also triggers `subtensor.get_current_block()` and there may be other similar cases. Could you please provide an estimate of the frequency of usage of these functions within your subnet (for miner and validator separately)?

Sure thing! On the validator end, `metagraph.sync` is called roughly every 150 seconds. `get_current_block` is also called by the validator twice when it sets weights--once before weights are set to determine if the last updated block was more than 100 blocks ago (this comparison happens every step, or roughly every ~30 seconds, and triggers a weight set if true), and once after weights are set to update the last updated block.

On the miner side, `metagraph.sync` is called roughly every 600 seconds. `get_current_block` is also called during the miner init and serves as a metric of when the miner was last updated but nowhere in the main loop itself.
